50–Female":"1350–Overleden","1380–1492":"1380–1492","–1492":"–1492","–Male":"Overleden","1320–Male":"1320–Overleden","1325–Female":"1325–Overleden","6 November 1386":"6 november 1386","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1320":"1320","1386":"1386","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1492":"1492","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Pinchbeck, Lincolnshire, England":"Pinchbeck, Lincolnshire, England","Whaplode, Lincolnshire, England":"Whaplode, Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"1345–6 November 1386":"1345–6 November 1386","1345–1386":"1345–1386","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1380–1492":"1380–1492","–1492":"–1492","–Male":"Deceased","1320–Male":"1320–Deceased","1325–Female":"1325–Deceased","6 November 1386":"6 November 1386","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1320":"1320","1386":"1386","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1492":"1492","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Pinchbeck, Lincolnshire, England":"Pinchbeck, Lincolnshire, England","Whaplode, Lincolnshire, England":"Whaplode, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pinchbeck","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Pinchbeck in Lincolnshire. The placename derives from the name of a local stream, named with Old English <i>pinc</i> ‘minnow’ + Old Norse <i>bekkr</i> ‘stream’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Sarsonne de Pinchbeck was born in 1345, in Pinchbeck, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Sir Thomas Sarsonne Lord of Pinchbeck, was 25 and his mother, Lady Thomas Sarsonne, was 20. He married Lady Joan Bawde in 1370, in Whaplode, Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died on 6 November 1386, in his hometown, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1345–6 November 1386":"1345–6. november 1386","1345–1386":"1345–1386","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1380–1492":"1380–1492","–1492":"–1492","–Male":"Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","6 November 1386":"6. november 1386","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1320":"1320","1386":"1386","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1492":"1492","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Pinchbeck, Lincolnshire, England":"Pinchbeck, Lincolnshire, England","Whaplode, Lincolnshire, England":"Whaplode, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1345–6 November 1386":"1345–6. marraskuuta 1386","1345–1386":"1345–1386","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1380–1492":"1380–1492","–1492":"–1492","–Male":"Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","6 November 1386":"6. marraskuuta 1386","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1320":"1320","1386":"1386","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1492":"1492","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Pinchbeck, Lincolnshire, England":"Pinchbeck, Lincolnshire, England","Whaplode, Lincolnshire, England":"Whaplode, Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"1345–6 November 1386":"1345–6 novembre 1386","1345–1386":"1345–1386","1350–Female":"1350–Décédée","1380–1492":"1380–1492","–1492":"–1492","–Male":"Décédé","1320–Male":"1320–Décédé","1325–Female":"1325–Décédée","6 November 1386":"6 novembre 1386","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1320":"1320","1386":"1386","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1492":"1492","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","Pinchbeck, Lincolnshire, England":"Pinchbeck, Lincolnshire, Angleterre","Whaplode, Lincolnshire, England":"Whaplode, Lincolnshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Sir Thomas Sarsonne de Pinchbeck est né en 1345, à Pinchbeck, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, son père, Sir Thomas Sarsonne Lord o